<Author>ChillaDaddy
<Content>Paradise in them thar Hills! My wife and I stayed at the Damai for 4 nights in March of 2007 as part of our trip to Bali. The Damai was the first port of call after the 30 odd hour journey from ther UK (the 2.5 hour car transfer was 4 hours long because religious icons were being carried through the villages as part of the forthcoming Hindu New Year festival, known as the Silent Day). The road from Lovina up to the Damai makes you wonder if you'll ever arrive but when you do its simply fabulous - quiet, out of the way and beautiful - perfect for couples wanting relaxation and some peace and quiet (those thinking of going with small or rowdy children please take note). We were greeted by a number of the staff (and a very welcome cocktail) and found that we were the only residents as it was low season and hence got a free upgrade , which was nice!!! We found it strange that after the first two days, other folk arrived - we were used to having the run of the place to ourselves but as the Damai has only 8 villas at present (more on the way down in the valley) you couldn't call it crowded!!! Nils ( the owner), Richard (the manager) and the staff were excellent - attentive when required and always smiling and happy to have a chat. The Balinese people are simply fantastic - seemingly always happy and ready for any opportunity to practice their English.The accommodation and food at the Damia were fantastic and even during the Silent Day celebrations when we were allowed no light by the local religious police we dined early by low candlelight and it was very romantic.Lovina in the low season was very quiet and backpackery so we visited once and left it at that, no least because the walk is all uphill back to the Damai!!!One thing to remember is that March is the end of the rainy seasion and hence it rains most days,usually during the night. In our 2 week stay in Bali we had two full days and nights of rain.All in all we found the Damai to be picture perfect and wouldn't hesitate to recommend it to anyone, though for the sake of those who want some peace and quiet I'd advise travellers with children who need entertaining that there isn't much to do except for the pool (which is fabulous - see photos) and hence it may not be their cup of tea.Next Stop - the Uma at Ubud - see our review there. 
